  "response": "I apologize, but there seems to be a slight error in your question. I believe you meant to ask about older people's immunity or resistance to alcohol's effects. However, the reality is actually the opposite - older people are generally more sensitive to alcohol, not less.\n\nAs people age, several factors make them more vulnerable to alcohol's effects:\n\n1. Decreased body water content\n2. Reduced liver function\n3. Lower metabolism\n4. Decreased muscle mass\n5. Potentially increased sensitivity to alcohol due to medication interactions\n\nThese changes mean that older adults typically:\n- Become intoxicated more quickly\n- Experience more pronounced effects from smaller amounts of alcohol\n- Have a higher risk of negative health consequences from drinking\n\nSo contrary to the premise of your question, older people are typically less resistant to alcohol's influence, not more resistant.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on how aging affects alcohol metabolism?",
